<div class="page-header"><h1>You live outside city limits. Here is what this means for you.</h1>
<p>This is a PfISD-wide vote, not a city decision. If you live within PfISD boundaries, you vote on this, regardless of whether you are inside or outside Pflugerville city limits. This page addresses the specific concerns of homeowners outside city limits.</p></div>
<div class="prose">

<h2>The cost for your household</h2>
<p>ACC's tax rate is $0.1034 per $100 of assessed valuation. ACC states this is the lowest community college tax rate in Texas. Here is what that looks like for common home values in the ETJ and exurban PfISD areas:</p>
<table class="compare-table">
<thead><tr><th>Home value</th><th>Annual ACC tax</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Daily</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>$300,000</td><td>~$305</td><td>~$25</td><td>~$0.84</td></tr>
<tr><td>$370,000 (median)</td><td>~$377</td><td>~$31</td><td>~$1.03</td></tr>
<tr><td>$450,000</td><td>~$460</td><td>~$38</td><td>~$1.26</td></tr>
<tr><td>$550,000</td><td>~$564</td><td>~$47</td><td>~$1.54</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--slate);">After standard $5,000 homestead exemption. Amounts rounded. <a href="/calculator/">Use the calculator</a> for your specific home value.</p>

<h2>If you are 65 or older, or have a disability</h2>
<p>ACC provides a $75,000 additional homestead exemption for homeowners 65+ or with disabilities, for a total exemption of $80,000. ACC also enacted a tax ceiling/freeze in 2021: once you qualify, your ACC tax is frozen at that year's amount and cannot increase, even if your property value rises. For a newly annexed area like PfISD, the ceiling begins the first year ACC taxes the property. It is not retroactive.</p>
<p>For a senior with a $370,000 home: taxable value is $290,000 after the $80,000 exemption. Annual ACC tax: approximately $300. That amount locks in and cannot go up. Additionally, seniors 65+ can take up to 6 credit hours per semester at ACC with tuition waived, on a space-available basis.</p>
<p>Source: <a href="https://offices.austincc.edu/finance-and-administration/property-taxes/" target="_blank">ACC Property Taxes</a>.</p>

<h2>"Nobody in my house is going to ACC"</h2>
<p>Fair objection. Here is the answer.</p>
<p>ACC trains the nurses who staff your clinics, the electricians who wire your home, the HVAC technicians who service your AC, and the IT workers your employer hires. Communities with in-district ACC access have those workers trained locally, at lower cost, and those workers stay local: 61% of community college graduates live within 50 miles of their college.</p>
<p>Texas community colleges contribute nearly $10 billion annually to the state economy. Every dollar spent produces $0.86 in additional economic activity. Workers with associate degrees earn approximately $8,788 more per year than high school diploma holders. That extra income circulates through your community.</p>
<p>And if anyone in your household ever wants a certification, a career change, or retraining, in-district access saves thousands of dollars. That option exists for the life of your homeownership, not just for this year.</p>

<h2>"This is the city making a decision for me"</h2>
<p>No. This is a vote by all registered voters in PfISD territory, including you. The city of Pflugerville does not control this process. The petition must be signed by PfISD residents. The vote is conducted among PfISD voters. Your vote counts equally whether you live inside city limits or outside.</p>

<h2>"My taxes are already too high"</h2>
<p>Understood. Pflugerville's combined property tax burden is significant. The ACC rate ($0.1034/$100) would add approximately $1.03 per day for the median homeowner. Compare that to one family member taking two ACC courses: $1,206 in savings in a single semester, more than 3x the annual tax. For households that use ACC even once, the return exceeds the cost in the first year.</p>
<p>For households that never attend: the annual cost is real but modest, and the community benefits (trained workforce, employer recruitment, economic activity) are documented across every Texas community that has joined a community college district.</p>

